Born William Anthony Parker on May 17, 1982 in Brugge, Belgium, Tony Parker was raised in France.

He began building his skills and decided to play the point guard position after considering his relatively small size for a basketball player (6'2") and speed.

In 2001, Parker was drafted by NBA's San Antonio Spurs.

As a backup player to Antonio Daniels, Parker made 77 regular season appearances in his rookie season.

He eventually led San Antonio in assists and steals by the end of the season and was named to the All-Rookie First Team for 2001Ã¢â¬â02.

Parker became San Antonio's starting point guard and playmaker in his sophomore season (2002-2003), where he won his first championship ring.

In the post season (2003), he went on to record two career bests in scoring and earned his first NBA championship ring when his team beat the New Jersey Nets 4Ã¢â¬â2 in the finals.

Parker, who scored a series-high 24.5 points, accompanied by a high field goal percentage of 56.8% and of 57.1% from three point range, was named the 2007 NBA Finals MVP, becoming the first European-born player to receive the award.

Parker set a career-high for assists per game in the 2007Ã¢â¬â08 regular seasons.

In the first round of the 2008 NBA Playoffs, the Spurs faced the Phoenix Suns, where Parker had an outstanding first round series, averaging nearly 30 points and 7 assists a game.

In the next round, Parker and teammate Manu Ginobili both scored 31 points to lead the Spurs to a 110-99 victory over the New Orleans Hornets in Game 3 of the Western Conference semifinals.

Parker's father, an American, also played basketball. His mother resides in Paris, though she is originally from Amsterdam.

Tony Parker is an All-Star guard for the San Antonio Spurs in the National Basketball Association . He plays point guard in the NBA and his statistics reflect his speed and effective outside shooting.

Parker was selected in the 2001 NBA draft by the San Antonio Spurs with the 28th pick.

On July 7, 2007, Parker married actress Eva Longoria.

Born in 1982, Anthony "Tony" Parker was in the French basketball league before entering the NBA Draft in 2001.

Currently, Parker is a point guard on the San Antonio Spurs, helping the Spurs win three NBA Championships in 2003, 2005 and 2007.

His two younger brothers, T.J. and Pierre, would go on to play basketball at professional and college levels, respectively.

After playing in the French minors for two seasons, Parker turned professional and signed with Paris Basket Racing in 1999.

